						<p class="text-lg text-justify">
							<strong class="text-xl text-blue-600">PRISM</strong> is
							Intersectionality Club’s online publication consisting of student
							works on identity and experience. This publication acts as a
							platform for the amplification of diverse voices, and as a medium
							through which students can share their individual stories.
						</p>
						<p class="text-lg text-justify mt-2">
							We decided on the name Prism because we believe such an object
							reflects the fundamental concept of intersectionality. Just as the
							unique qualities of a prism come from its overlap of colors
							within, every individual’s identities and experiences intersect
							and affect their story. The name is also inspired by civil rights
							advocate Kimberlé Crenshaw’s quote that intersectionality is a
							"prism, for seeing the way in which various forms of inequality
							often operate together and exacerbate each other.”
						</p>

						<h1 class="text-4xl text-red-600 font-black py-2">
							Submission Guidelines
						</h1>
						<p class="text-lg text-justify">
							We recognize that identities intersect and are fundamentally
							interconnected, making every individual different in their own
							unique way. We would like to highlight individual experiences and
							provide an online platform with which everyone can share their
							voices, opinions, and perspectives. In order to make using this
							platform a comfortable experience for everyone, here are the
							guidelines for submission:
							<ol class="indent-4 text-base">
								<li>
									Submissions may take any form: painting, photography, short
									films, personal narrative, poetry, journalistic articles, etc.
								</li>
								<li>
									For writing pieces, you may use first person, because it is
									your own narrative!
								</li>
								<li>
									Word limit: Literary works should not exceed the 3000 word
									limit.
								</li>
								<li>
									Do not appropriate content that is not yours. In other words,
									use your own experience and ideas rather than resorting to
									plagiarism.
								</li>
								<li>
									Give your piece a title---it will draw the attention of the
									reader/viewer!
								</li>
								<li>
									If you choose to remain anonymous, please let the editors know
									your preference.
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
