			<h1 id="quiet" class="text-4xl font-black py-6">
				the quiet by Audrey Tang
			</h1>
			<p class="text-base">
				11:54pm<br />
				<br />
				 it starts off as a hum &ndash; a low, reverberating purr at the base of
				the throat &ndash; before it snaps, rubber-band like, and roars so
				loudly it pierces through her ears and straight into her head. then, as
				abruptly as it started, it stops, and the engine rumbles away into the
				night.<br />
				<br />
				 the doppler effect, she remembers dimly. an image of a hand-drawn car
				with penciled rings flaring out around it flashes behind her closed
				eyelids. that stupid physics concept we learned last lesson where the
				car is moving towards you&#8230; then away&#8230; and the observed
				frequency increases while the object&rsquo;s sound frequency remains
				constant or something. the car on the paper expands and morphs into a
				plane, then a bird, then a boat, and she's long gone, floating among
				light waves and gravity and convoluted little equations.<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				 12:32am<br />
				<br />
				 the melody hasn&rsquo;t stopped. the melody doesn&rsquo;t stop. i have
				an exam tomorrow, she pleads with it. they reply with crescendoing waves
				and cascading thunder. the storm spreads to her feet and she feels the
				familiar, numb tingling, like ants biting into her calves and thighs and
				she just needs to move. so she moves to hold the storm at bay. she
				tosses and turns on the bed as it bobs atop roiling waves. <br />
				<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				 07:30am<br />
				<br />
				 Nobody&rsquo;s there yet. Of course nobody is &mdash; she always makes
				sure to wake half an hour before schedule, to be at school half an hour
				before classes start, just in case. She&rsquo;s meticulously checked
				every item in her bag, thrice, just in case. <br />
				<br />
				 Red, raw bite marks dapple her lips, and her nails are chipped and
				jagged. The clock ticks. She tugs at her eyelashes. It&rsquo;s the dread
				that keeps her on the edge of her seat &mdash; the dread that&rsquo;s at
				the tip of her tongue, at the edge of the precipice, teetering, waiting
				to crash over her. What are you so afraid of? She asks herself. She
				doesn&rsquo;t answer. She doesn&rsquo;t know. All she knows is the rain
				pounding away in her head, wahlah-wahlah-wahlah, and that familiar
				sensation of the screw wounding up in her chest. She clutches the phone
				in her hand so tightly her knuckles turn bone-white. Just in case.<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				 3:34pm<br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;90. i got a 90.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 i mean, really, what&rsquo;d she expect? she&rsquo;d barely studied for
				this test. actually, she had. she&rsquo;d studied so, so hard, starting
				when the clock struck twelve until the first streaks of daylight
				filtered through the blinds, but she had just been so tired. the
				rustling leaves had thundered in her temples for hours straight, and
				she&rsquo;d felt like she was bobbing up and down on driftwood, with
				crackling static blaring in her ears. <br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;well, that&rsquo;s wonderful! well done!&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 he&rsquo;s a nosy man with red-framed glasses and a clipboard in his
				hands. he&rsquo;s nosy because all he does is pry and pry and pry, in
				order to fill the empty space gaping in his own life. he doesn&rsquo;t
				get it. <br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;it&rsquo;s not that good of a result.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 she fiddles absentmindedly with the grass seahorse in her hands.
				there&rsquo;s a small dip in between the snout and the neck that she
				likes, because the rasp &mdash; the shkk &mdash; feels particularly good
				against the pad of her thumb. shkk. shkk. shkk.<br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;i think you're a little too hard on yourself sometimes, but i
				assure you that you are perfectly fine. an average person doesn&rsquo;t
				do as well as you do. in fact, you are gifted!&rdquo; he laughs as if
				he&rsquo;s said something particularly clever. &ldquo;so you see, you
				have nothing to worry about.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;okay.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 shkk. shkk.<br />
				<br />
				 he slides a thin stack of documents across the table towards her.
				&ldquo;here are your results from last week. you can take a look when
				you have time.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 she doesn&rsquo;t want to wait, though, because nausea is rising up in
				her throat and threatening to crush her chest in its fist. she snatches
				the papers, and the first thing that pops up in her vision &mdash; the
				one bolded, italicized, underlined word, right smack at the bottom of
				the documents &mdash;<br />
				<br />
				 ineligible.<br />
				<br />
				 she laughs. then she laughs again. then she laughs harder and doubles
				over. she doesn&rsquo;t care that she&rsquo;s in this strange,
				marble-tiled room with fluorescent lights beaming down on her and a
				stranger sitting across the table from her. she doesn&rsquo;t care that
				the stranger is currently gazing at her with some sort of paternalistic,
				patronizing concern in his eyes.<br />
				<br />
				 she straightens up.<br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;thanks for the diagnosis, dr. verdi,&rdquo; she tells him,
				&ldquo;i know you tried.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				 4:19pm<br />
				<br />
				 He meets her by the pond next to the woods next to the school.
				It&rsquo;s a good distance away &mdash; close enough to be convenient,
				yet far enough so that stragglers heading home at dusk don&rsquo;t
				stumble upon them. The same figure, the same pond, the same posture,
				every Thursday. Strangely enough, his still form reminds her of that
				series of 25 paintings some artist did of haystacks, each painting
				differing by just the slightest change in mood or in lighting or in
				shadows. The only constant thing in those paintings are the haystacks,
				which stay exactly the same across every canvas; they just squat there
				amongst the rustling fields, stoically, tauntingly, almost like they
				want to piss her off with their stillness.<br />
				<br />
				 Anyway. There he stands, a hooded figure silhouetted against a
				whispering backdrop. He&rsquo;s nervous. She can tell. His eyes &mdash;
				round, gray, owl-like eyes that peek out from behind thick-framed
				glasses &mdash; dart from left to right to left again before finally
				landing on her.<br />
				<br />
				 &ldquo;Dude, my mom caught me sneaking out and made me tell her what I
				was doing,&rdquo; is the first thing he says when she nears.
				&ldquo;You&rsquo;re lucky I&rsquo;m a good liar.&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 She doesn&rsquo;t respond. Maybe she doesn&rsquo;t have the will to.
				The rustling of the trees is crescendoing, somehow, cluttering her ears,
				extending directly through her temples and into her brain and her eyes
				and her nose and hemming in on her, and she&rsquo;s getting really
				annoyed. <br />
				<br />
				 Noticing the long lapse of silence, he shifts uncomfortably, kicking at
				the pebbles near his feet. &ldquo;Um. So. Are they helping?&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 Yes. No. Kind of. But she doesn&rsquo;t say any of this out loud
				because the rustling is overwhelming, and she just wants him to shut up.
				So she nods and schools her features into a smile. Maybe it looks more
				like a grimace &mdash; she hopes it doesn&rsquo;t. Either way, relief
				slackens his face. &ldquo;Okay. That&rsquo;s good. Just be careful of
				the side effects, okay? You&rsquo;re going to tell me if you start
				feeling any, right?&rdquo;<br />
				<br />
				 She barely registers what he&rsquo;s saying, but she nods again anyway.
				She extends her hand, palm up, and he drops the bottle in her hand. He
				waves to her, she waves to him; he turns and walks north, she turns and
				heads south. Two strangers finding their way home.<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				<br />
				 8:44pm<br />
				<br />
				 she kicks the week-old ramen cup out of the way and watches it skid
				across the room, trembling fingers fumbling with the lock; back pressed
				against the door, she slides down until her knees hit the ground and
				rests her cheek against the cool stone wall, crushed to the floor by a
				suffocating weight.<br />
				<br />
				 not this again.<br />
				<br />
				 dazedly, she tries to calm her mind, but the waterfall crashes down
				again, drowning all coherent thought in a raging torrent. she opens her
				mouth, tries to speak to herself, and all that escapes is a muffled
				choke that grows into a whine. her hands push into her hair and she
				tugs, and tugs, but even the pinpricks of pain that jab into her skull
				don&rsquo;t snap her out of it. <br />
				<br />
				 her unfocused eyes slide around the room until they zero in on a gray,
				tattered tapestry that&rsquo;s dangling from the wall. the cord that
				ties it to the wall is fraying, unraveling, and something about that
				casual, sluggish destruction pushes her over the edge. with two steps,
				she&rsquo;s across the room &mdash; she wrenches it off, she enjoys the
				snap it makes as it tears &mdash; then she&rsquo;s ripping the intricate
				fabric work up with her hands, glistening beads are clattering to the
				floor like a cascade of iridescent hail and they hurt just like actual
				hail too, pinging off her feet and her hands until she finally hurls the
				tapestry away from her with all the force she can muster. it falls to
				the floor and flutters there, brokenly, until she stomps on it. it goes
				still.<br />
				<br />
				 her blood is roaring red in her eyes, heartbeat churning in her ears,
				when she starts to smile. she laughs out loud, but it&rsquo;s a quiet
