			<h1 id="art" class="text-4xl font-black py-6">
				The Art of Language by Mahika Varma
			</h1>
			<p class="text-base">
				Most people go through their lives wishing they learned another
				language. This stems from many things, like interest in a television
				show, such as Japanese in Alice in Borderland, or increasing
				employability, like French in Canada. Wanting to know a language other
				than English is common because most feel that English is plain and
				uninteresting. Everyone knows English, right?<br />
				<br />
				 I often hear: &ldquo;You know French? That is crazy!&rdquo; and I
				appreciate the admiration, but I notice that this is not the reaction I
				receive when someone finds out I speak Hindi. I am expected to know
				Hindi, just like you are expected to speak English, and it is,
				therefore, unimpressive. Never mind I was born in Canada and went to an
				English-speaking school. Never mind I had to learn Hindi for six hours
				every Saturday. It is just not impressive.<br />
				<br />
				 People often forget that understanding any language is a feat because
				they are so enamoured with Western European dialects. When a French
				immigrant knows French, they are treated like a God. When a British
				immigrant has an accent, they become rather popular. This is not to say
				the French should be demeaned, or that we should disregard the
				fascinating accent of the British, but we must recognize our own
				hypocrisy. When a Mexican immigrant speaks Spanish, or a Chinese
				immigrant speaks accented English, we, as a society, treat them
				differently. Now, our gut reaction may be to deny this, but it is true.<br
				/><br />
				 In 2018, the Pew Research Center found that 38% of Hispanic or Latino
				people in America &ldquo;have recently experienced one of four incidents
				&ndash; being called offensive names, being told to go back to their
				home country, being criticized for speaking Spanish in public, or
				experiencing discrimination or unfair treatment because they are
				Hispanic&rdquo; (Lopez et al., 2018). Similarly, The University of
				Queensland found that in the hiring process, there was no discrimination
				between a candidate with American-accented English versus
				British-accented English, but there was heavy prejudice in favour of
				candidates with American-accented English over those with
				Chinese-accented English (Spence, et al., 2022). Evidently, the
				qualifications of these candidates did not play a role in the judgements
				made about them. Speaking Chinese-accented English simply implied that
				the candidate was uneducated and not fit for the job, whereas speaking
				British-accented English did not hinder an applicant&rsquo;s chances.<br
				/><br />
				 Why is it that we hate &ldquo;foreign&rdquo;-accented English so much?
				Some argue that it is hard to understand, and others argue that if
				someone has immigrated, they may have less education, but neither of
				these assertions makes much sense. That is, of course, logically
				speaking, but much prejudice is not based on logic, but on assumptions
				that are made about certain groups. When someone speaks with
				accented-English, a picture of stereotypes will pop into our heads,
				whether that be intentional or otherwise. Perhaps when we hear a British
				accent, we think of royalty and education because of the monarchy and
				riches. On the other hand, perhaps when we hear an Indian accent, we
				think of corruption and dirt, because last week we saw a news piece on
				CNN about the Indian government&rsquo;s faults. These images and
				stereotypes paint severely different pictures of these two groups and
				systemically hinder their chances for success.<br /><br />
				 So, what does this tell us? The problem is not that someone speaks a
				different language, or someone has a different accent. It is that
				someone speaks a language or has an accent with which we do not feel
				comfortable. To combat this implicit bias, systemic changes must be
				made, which is not an easy task, but accepting and identifying the issue
				is the first step. <br />
			</p>

