			<h1 id="cantoneese" class="text-4xl font-black py-6">
				Cantonese by Audrey Tang
			</h1>
			<p class="text-base">
				Loud, crass, lively, flip-flopping off the tongue. There are nine tones.
				Nine subtle fluctuations of the tongue and the throat as the old women
				at the wet market argue like their lives depend on the price of a trout.
				The bickering escalates. Well, that&rsquo;s not pretty. I try to do the
				opposite of focus &mdash; I stop concentrating, I try to disassociate my
				memory from my hearing &mdash; and for just one moment, the
				women&rsquo;s voices sound like jabbering chaos. <br />
				<br />
				 Unlike Italian, Cantonese does not flow through the ears like water.
				Unlike French, it does not soothe like aloe on sun-scarred skin. But the
				familiar up-down-right-left bounce of the dialect makes me laugh. In no
				other language will you find the casual, incomprehensible vulgarity with
				which we Hong Kongers speak. <br />
				<br />
				 But there is beauty in the words. Our names hold meaning and love. Mine
				means blue sky. To be free like a bird in the blue skies. To remain
				sturdy and unyielding like a pilot in the blue skies. To be joyful and
				cloudless and forever full of sunlight in the blue skies.<br /><br />

				 Talking in Cantonese is how you should sing, my vocal teacher sometimes
				says. Always going, never stopping, sometimes boisterous, sometimes subdued,
				but never breaking the line. The legato. Because no matter how staccato Cantonese
				sounds, the words form steady rivulets, just like how a breath is constantly
				sustained, how a soft palate is continuously lifted. There must be tension
				between the palate and the back of the tongue. Just like in Cantonese. So,
				Cantonese is singing.<br /><br />

				 Cantonese is when your father yells at the TV about the state of the economy.
				Cantonese is your grandmother lecturing you over a round of mahjong and dinners.
				It is chattering to your mother about the effects of the patriarchy in Asian
				families. It is memorizing and reading the most heartrending poetry in classrooms
				while your teacher teaches you about the romanticism of Li Bai or Du Mu.
				It is also cursing with the filthiest words known to civilization in the
				railway station while knowing nobody will bat an eye.<br /><br />

				 I latch onto Cantonese tightly during winters and summers.
			</p>

